# Errors

The launcher and MCP wrappers emit a single JSON line to stderr on failure
that conforms to `schemas/error.schema.json`.

## Stable Codes

| Code | Exit | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `E0000` | 0 | Success |
| `E0002` | 2 | Input validation failure |
| `E0003` | 3 | Required dependency missing |
| `E0004` | 4 | GitHub setup failure |
| `E0005` | 5 | Project scaffold failure |
| `E0006` | 6 | MCP registration failure |
| `E0007` | 7 | MCP config generation failure |
| `E0008` | 8 | MCP schedule seeding failure |
| `E0009` | 9 | Validation failure |
| `E0010` | 10 | Unsafe operation blocked |
| `E1001` | 9 | Schema incompatible with current compat-mode |
| `E1002` | 9 | Queue invariant violated |
| `E2001` | 6 | Out-of-scope project access |
| `E2002` | 6 | Approval required |
| `E2003` | 6 | Policy denied action |

## Reading an error line

```json
{"code":"E0009","correlation_id":"...","exit_code":9,"hint":"Run scripts/validate_launch.sh","message":"Validation failure"}
```

The `correlation_id` should be quoted in any incident or runbook entry.
